## Code Review: COMP018 (List.Item.Detail inline detail panel)

### 1. BUG: Animation replays on every re-render when selecting different list items

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.tsx` (line 125) and `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.scss` (line 26)

The `.list-detail-panel` div has `animation: list-detail-slide-in $transition-slow ease-out both` applied unconditionally. Every time the `detail` prop changes (i.e., user navigates to a different list item and a new `<Detail>` is rendered), React re-renders the `<div className="list-detail-panel">` with the same child but different content. Because the parent div is stable (not re-keyed), the animation will **not** replay on content change -- which is correct. However, if `showDetail` transitions from `false` to `true`, the entire branch mounts fresh and the animation fires -- also correct.

**But**: if you ever add a `key` prop to force re-mount on item change (a common follow-up), the slide-in will replay on every selection. Worth adding a comment-level awareness or using a class toggle (`list-detail-panel--entering`) applied only on initial mount. This is a latent fragility, not a current bug.

### 2. BUG: `showDetail` and `detail` are semantically redundant -- one should derive from the other

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.tsx` (lines 17-18)

```tsx
showDetail?: boolean;
detail?: ReactNode;
```

The caller in `App.tsx` (line 936) already does `showDetail={!!detail}`. The `showDetail` prop is always derived from whether `detail` is truthy. This means:

- A consumer could pass `showDetail={true}` with `detail={undefined}`, rendering an empty panel with a border and no content.
- A consumer could pass `showDetail={false}` with `detail={<Detail .../>}`, silently discarding the detail.

**Fix:** Remove `showDetail` and derive it internally: `const showDetail = detail != null`. This eliminates an invalid-state hole. If you need `showDetail` as an explicit toggle (e.g., to animate the panel away while keeping the ReactNode mounted for transition), then at minimum add runtime validation or a JSDoc explaining the contract.

### 3. ISSUE: `overflow-y: auto` on `.list` is inherited by `.list--with-detail` but the panel itself has `overflow: hidden`

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.scss`

```scss
.list {
  flex: 1;
  overflow-y: auto;
  padding: 0 $space-2;
}

.list--with-detail {
  flex: 0 0 40%;
  min-width: 0;
}

.list-detail-panel {
  flex: 1;
  min-width: 0;
  overflow: hidden; // <-- this clips the Detail's own scroll
}
```

The `.list-detail-panel` has `overflow: hidden`, but the `Detail` component's `.detail__content` has `overflow-y: auto` (line 18 of `detail.scss`). This works **only** because `.detail` has `flex: 1` and `overflow: hidden`, and `.detail__content` handles its own scroll. However, `overflow: hidden` on `.list-detail-panel` combined with no explicit `height` constraint could clip content in edge cases where `.detail` doesn't properly flex.

**Fix:** Change `.list-detail-panel` to `overflow-y: auto` or, better, add `display: flex; flex-direction: column;` so that the child `.detail` can properly fill and scroll:

```scss
.list-detail-panel {
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  flex: 1;
  min-width: 0;
  border-left: 1px solid var(--border-100);
  animation: list-detail-slide-in $transition-slow ease-out both;
}
```

This ensures the Detail component's flex layout chains correctly from the panel container.

### 4. ISSUE: Missing ARIA landmark on the detail panel

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.tsx` (line 125)

```tsx
<div className="list-detail-panel">{detail}</div>
```

The `Detail` component already has `role="region"` and `aria-label="Detail view"`, so this is partially covered. However, the wrapping `.list-detail-split` container provides no ARIA context to indicate it is a split view. Screen readers won't understand the spatial relationship.

**Fix:** Add `role="complementary"` or `aria-label` to `.list-detail-panel`:

```tsx
<div className="list-detail-panel" role="complementary" aria-label="Item detail">
  {detail}
</div>
```

### 5. ISSUE: The `prefers-reduced-motion` media query is not respected

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.scss` (lines 29-38)

The slide-in animation does not respect `prefers-reduced-motion`. Users with motion sensitivity will see the translateX + opacity animation.

**Fix:**

```scss
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .list-detail-panel {
    animation: none;
  }
}
```

Check if the rest of the codebase already has a global reduced-motion reset. If not, this should be added at least for this new animation.

### 6. CLEANUP: Hardcoded 40% width ratio should be a token

**File:** `/Users/anotonio.silva/antonio/lol/src/components/list/list.scss` (line 10)

```scss
.list--with-detail {
  flex: 0 0 40%;
}
```

The project convention from `_tokens.scss` is to use variables for all design tokens. The 40%/60% split ratio is a design decision that should be a token (e.g., `$list-detail-split-ratio: 40%`), especially since the Detail component's internal metadata split also uses 40%/60% (in `detail.scss` lines 11-13). If these need to stay in sync, a shared token prevents drift.

